text:
My Honest Review of the Bajaj Chetak 3501 ‚Äì Disappointed & Frustrated

I purchased my Bajaj Chetak 3501 on 30th April with high expectations, but the experience has been nothing short of disappointing. The very next day after purchase, the scooter stopped working completely. I had to take it to the service centre, and it took them two full days just to fix the issue.

Things only got worse from there. After just 1,800 km of usage, the main battery cells failed. On a full charge, I was getting a range of barely 50‚Äì60 km, far below the promised performance. My scooter was stuck in the service centre for days because they told me it would take 20 days to replace the battery.

What‚Äôs more concerning is that I‚Äôm not the only one facing this problem. I saw multiple Chetak scooters parked at the service centre with the exact same issue.

On top of that, the TechPack feature ‚Äî for which I paid an extra ‚Çπ5,000 ‚Äî is extremely glitchy. Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn‚Äôt. And honestly, kya fayda TechPack ke liye 5000 dene ka jab wo service chal hi nahi rahi hai? Instead of selling scooters with half-functional features, Bajaj should focus on keeping them properly maintained. If you can‚Äôt ensure these features work reliably, it‚Äôs better to sell a scooter without them than frustrate customers.

This is my first experience with Bajaj and Chetak, and unfortunately, it has been terrible so far. The brand‚Äôs lack of reliability and poor after-sales support has completely ruined my trust. If I could go back, I would have chosen an Ather instead.

Update ‚Äì 7th August: My battery has finally been replaced with a new one. I‚Äôll update this review if the same problem happens again, but for now, my advice remains the same: Don‚Äôt buy the Chetak right now. Until Bajaj addresses these battery, service, and TechPack issues, it‚Äôs not worth the risk.
